revision.text:
[[File:UlsterMuseumPrehistoryMe (9) (cropped).JPG|thumb|The Moss-side hoard of Mesolithic Bann flake tools and blades, [[Ulster Museum]].<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/9Nc-qR6IShGJlDPaS495AQ BBC], ''[[A History of the World in 100 Objects]]''</ref>]]
[[File:Armagh County Museum, Bann Flakes.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Four Bann flakes on display in Armagh County Museum.]]
A '''Bann flake''' is a large, butt-trimmed, leaf-shaped [[lithic blade]] of [[flint]] or [[chert]], dating from the Late [[Mesolithic]] period of [[prehistoric Ireland]], from around 4500 BC onwards.  They are named after the [[river Bann]] in Northern Ireland where large numbers have been found.<ref>Wallace and O'Floinn, 45</ref>   The term is rather variably defined, and the uses of the flakes probably varied considerably, with many being all-purpose tools, and perhaps weapons. Some were probably used as spear heads attached to wooden shafts, despite many being rather heavy for this.<ref>[http://www.mountsandel.com/teachers/meso_later.asp "The Later Mesolithic: 5500-3500 BC"], Mount Sandel</ref>  

They are part of the Bann culture assemblage. Peter Woodman of [[University College Cork]] defines them as large flakes without a significant [[Tang (tools)|tang]], with only light [[Retouch (lithics)|retouch]].<ref>[http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803095445477 "Bann flake"], in ''The Concise Oxford Dictionary of Archaeology''</ref>  They come in two forms: elongated or laminar forms less than 3.2&nbsp;cm across, or wider leaf shapes having only very peripheral retouch at the butt. 

