The '''Chelleo-Acheulean''' is a [[Palaeolithic]] stone tool industry that marks a transitional stage between the [[Chellean]] ([[Abbevillian]] or [[Oldowan]]) and the [[Acheulean]].<ref name="F.G.S.1956">{{cite book|author=M.C. BURKIT |title=THE OLD STONE AGE A STUDY OF PALAEOLITHIC TIMES|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NtYy2qa6y_AC|accessdate=9 September 2012|year=1956}}</ref><ref name="Alimen1957">{{cite book|author=[[Henriette Alimen]]|title=The prehistory of Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=efsEAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=9 September 2012|year=1957|publisher=Hutchinson}}</ref><ref name="Daniels1989">{{cite book|author=Norman Daniels|title=Reading Rawls: Critical Studies on Rawls' "A Theory of Justice"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u26mAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA8|accessdate=9 September 2012|date=May 1989|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-1716-8|pages=8–}}</ref> [[Louis Leakey]] identified eleven stages of development in the Chelleo-Acheulean "hand [[axe]] culture" in [[Africa]].<ref name="Robertshaw1990">{{cite book|author=Peter Robertshaw|title=A History of African Archaeology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cN1Tf1DncbgC&pg=PA81|accessdate=9 September 2012|year=1990|publisher=J. Currey|isbn=978-0-85255-065-6|pages=81–}}</ref>
